"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Nehemiah chapter 13
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-nehemiah-13-13.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/nehemiah.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/nehemiah.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/nehemiah.json (chs 1-9 for style/terminology)

Key Christological decisions:
- Tobiah's room cleansing (vv4-9): type of Christ's temple cleansing (John 2:13-17)
- Balaam's curse→blessing (v2): anticipates Gal 3:13 curse reversal at the cross
- Four zāḵar prayers (vv14,22,29,31): contrast with Christ as the basis of divine remembrance
- Solomon precedent (v26): Christ as greater-than-Solomon whose wisdom is never corrupted
- High priest's grandson expelled (v28): contrast with Christ as holy, blameless, unstained high priest
- Final verse (v31): last words of book echo the thief on the cross (Luke 23:42) — both appeal to divine remembrance
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEH13 = {
    "13": {
        "1": "<p>A theme: the reading of Moses's Law on 'that day' and the discovery of the Ammonite/Moabite exclusion (Deut 23:3–5) places this chapter under the same Torah-renewal program that began in ch. 8. The exclusion law preserved the covenant community's distinctiveness — the same concern that drives Paul's warning against being 'unequally yoked' (2 Cor 6:14). In Christ the boundary is reconstituted: not by ethnic exclusion but by the Spirit (Eph 2:11–22), where Ammonites and Moabites who trust Christ are more fully inside than circumcised Israelites who reject him.</p>",
        "2": "<p>A theme: Balaam was hired to curse Israel but God turned the curse into a blessing. This reversal is one of the defining patterns of the biblical narrative that reaches its apex at the cross — where what looked like curse and defeat (Deut 21:23; Gal 3:13) was in fact the ultimate blessing for all who believe. Paul cites the Deut 21 text explicitly: 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us' (Gal 3:13). The Balaam episode is the earliest canonical anticipation of this curse-to-blessing reversal.</p>",
        "3": "<p>A theme: the separation from 'all those of foreign descent' (<em>ʿēreḇ</em>, the mixed multitude) after hearing the Torah mirrors the covenant-community boundary-maintenance that runs throughout Israel's history. In Christ, the boundary is maintained not by ethnicity but by faith and the Spirit — the 'mixed multitude' that attaches to Israel is transformed rather than expelled (Acts 2:5–12; Rev 7:9). The principle of holy distinction remains; the basis changes from bloodline to new creation (Gal 6:15).</p>",
        "4": "<p>A shadow: Eliashib the high priest formed an alliance with Tobiah the Ammonite, using the sacred storerooms as his residence. The high priest who should have guarded the temple's purity instead opened it to the enemy. This shadow points negatively to Christ: where Eliashib defiled his office through corrupt alliance, Christ the Great High Priest is 'holy, blameless, unstained, separated from sinners' (Heb 7:26) — his priestly house can never be surrendered to the adversary.</p>",
        "5": "<p>A shadow: the storeroom that held grain offerings, incense, vessels, tithes, and portions for the Levites — the material infrastructure of temple worship — was cleared out and given to Tobiah. The profanation of what was set apart for God is the shadow sin that the rest of the chapter undoes. In Christ, the temple is replaced by his body (John 2:21) and by the community of the Spirit (1 Cor 3:16–17). The NT equivalent of giving Tobiah a storeroom would be using the church as a vehicle for worldly alliance — Paul warns against exactly this (2 Cor 6:14–18).</p>",
        "6": "<p>A theme: Nehemiah's absence from Jerusalem led to the deterioration of the reforms. The theme of the absent leader and the community's drift is a recurring biblical pattern: Moses absent on Sinai produces the golden calf (Exod 32); Christ's ascension produces the question of how the community maintains its covenant fidelity in his absence. The NT answer is the Spirit (John 16:7) — the Paraclete as the present leadership of the absent Christ, guarding the church from the 'Tobiahs' of every generation.</p>",
        "7": "<p>A revelation of God: Nehemiah's return to Jerusalem and immediate discovery of 'the evil Eliashib had done' reveals God's providential oversight of his house — evil done within the temple is not hidden from God's appointed governor. In Christ, this oversight is perfected: Jesus sees the temple corruption and acts (John 2:13–17; Rev 2:1–3:22 — the letters to the churches begin 'I know your works'). No profanation of the sacred space is unnoticed.</p>",
        "8": "<p>A type: Nehemiah was 'deeply displeased' (<em>wayyēraʿ lî məʾōḏ</em>) and threw Tobiah's belongings out of the room. This is the most direct type of Christ's temple cleansing in the book: Jesus overturned the tables of the money-changers and drove out those who made his Father's house a marketplace (John 2:13–17; Matt 21:12–13). John interprets the cleansing via Ps 69:9: 'Zeal for your house will consume me.' Nehemiah's act is the preparatory shadow; Christ's is the definitive cleansing.</p>",
        "9": "<p>A shadow: after the expulsion, Nehemiah ordered the rooms cleansed (<em>ṭāhēr</em>, H2891) and restored the temple vessels and offerings to their proper place. The sequence — expulsion then purification then restoration — follows the same pattern as the Day of Atonement (Lev 16) and as the NT's account of Christ's saving work: he removed sin, purified the conscience (Heb 9:14), and restored access to the Father (Eph 2:18). The cleansed room is a domestic-scale image of what Christ accomplishes on a cosmic scale.</p>",
        "10": "<p>A revelation of God: the Levites and singers fled to their own fields when their portions were not given — they could not sustain their sacred calling without material support. The theme that God's servants require provision for their ministry is affirmed in the NT (1 Cor 9:9–14; 1 Tim 5:17–18 — both citing the ox-muzzling law). Christ himself provided for his disciples (John 6:1–13; Luke 9:3–4) and the early church organized systematic support for its ministers (Acts 4:34–35; Gal 6:6).</p>",
        "11": "<p>A revelation of God: Nehemiah's charge against the officials — 'Why is the house of God forsaken?' — is also God's charge. The house of God being forsaken through neglect and self-interest is a covenantal crisis. In Christ, the house of God is never forsaken: 'I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it' (Matt 16:18). The scattered Levites restored to their posts are a shadow of the Good Shepherd gathering the scattered sheep (John 10:16; 11:52).</p>",
        "12": "<p>A theme: the tithes of grain, wine, and oil brought to the storehouses after Nehemiah's reform represents covenant faithfulness being restored. The tithe principle — returning to God a portion of what God has given — runs throughout the OT (Gen 14:20; Deut 14:22–29; Mal 3:10) and in the NT is fulfilled in the pattern of radical generosity: 'God loves a cheerful giver' (2 Cor 9:7). In Christ, the tithe is not abolished but transcended — the standard is not ten percent but 'as much as each had need' (Acts 2:45).</p>",
        "13": "<p>A theme: Nehemiah's appointment of faithful stewards — 'these men were regarded as faithful' (<em>neʾĕmānîm</em>, H539) — for distributing portions reflects the NT theology of stewardship. 'It is required of stewards that they be found trustworthy' (1 Cor 4:2). Christ himself is described as a 'merciful and faithful high priest' (Heb 2:17) and as 'faithful over God's house as a son' (Heb 3:6) — the supreme embodiment of the faithfulness that Nehemiah sought in his treasurers.</p>",
        "14": "<p>A theme: the first zāḵar prayer — 'Remember me, O my God, for this, and do not blot out my good deeds' — grounds the appeal in personal covenant faithfulness. Nehemiah asks to be remembered by his works. This contrasts with the grace-basis of NT remembrance: on the cross, the thief asks simply 'remember me when you come into your kingdom' (Luke 23:42) with no works to appeal to. In Christ, divine remembrance is grounded not in our deeds but in his: our names written in the Lamb's book of life (Rev 21:27) by grace.</p>",
        "15": "<p>A shadow: the Sabbath violations — treading winepresses, hauling goods, selling food on the Sabbath — represent the erosion of the covenant sign of rest. The Sabbath pointed forward to the rest Christ provides (Heb 4:1–11): 'There remains a Sabbath rest for the people of God' (Heb 4:9). Jesus's Sabbath controversies (Matt 12:1–14; John 5:1–18) do not abolish the Sabbath's Christological trajectory but fulfill it: he is Lord of the Sabbath (Matt 12:8) because he is the rest to which the Sabbath pointed.</p>",
        "16": "<p>A theme: the Tyrians selling fish and merchandise on the Sabbath within Jerusalem represent the penetration of commercial-pagan culture into the covenant community's sacred time. Nehemiah's confrontation of this infiltration mirrors Paul's warning that 'the world' has its own logic that corrupts the community's calendar of holiness (Col 2:16–17). In Christ, 'the substance belongs to Christ' — the shadows of Sabbath and festival all find their fulfillment in him rather than in external regulations.</p>",
        "17": "<p>A revelation of God: Nehemiah confronting the nobles with 'What is this evil thing you are doing?' recalls the prophetic confrontation pattern throughout the OT — Nathan to David (2 Sam 12:7), Elijah to Ahab (1 Kgs 21:20), John the Baptist to Herod (Matt 14:4). In Christ, the ultimate prophetic confrontation of covenant-breaking comes from one who is himself the covenant (Isa 42:6) — his words 'What is this evil?' carry divine authority because he is the Word through whom the covenant was given.</p>",
        "18": "<p>A revelation of God: Nehemiah's appeal to historical memory — 'your ancestors did the same, and God brought disaster on us and this city' — uses the exile as a warning against repeating Sabbath violation. The theology of historical judgment as covenant warning (Deut 28–30) is absorbed into the NT (1 Cor 10:1–13: 'these things happened as examples for us'). In Christ, the exile's curse has been absorbed (Gal 3:13) and the warning is no longer 'disaster will come' but 'wrath has already been averted by the cross.'</p>",
        "19": "<p>A shadow: the gate-closing at dusk before the Sabbath created a temporal boundary — inside the walls was sacred time; outside was commercial time. Jesus as the gate/door (John 10:7, 9) is the true boundary between the sacred and the profane: 'I am the door; if anyone enters through me, he will be saved.' The Sabbath gate that Nehemiah shuts at dusk is a temporal shadow of the eternal boundary that Christ himself constitutes — those who enter through him enter into rest.</p>",
        "20": "<p>A theme: the merchants who camped outside the wall one or two times, hoping the gates would open, represent those who press the boundary of the sacred without entering it. The image of waiting outside the gate resonates with Christ's parable of the ten virgins (Matt 25:10–12) — the door is shut and those outside call 'Lord, Lord, open to us.' The patience and persistence of the merchants outside Nehemiah's wall is a shadow of the earnest seeking that is the right posture before the door that Christ opens.</p>",
        "21": "<p>A revelation of God: Nehemiah's warning 'if you do this again, I will use force against you' — and the merchants' compliance — reveals that the covenant order is maintained by clear authority backed by real consequence. In Christ, the authority is both gentle invitation ('come to me,' Matt 11:28) and final judgment (Matt 25:41). The merchants' voluntary withdrawal after Nehemiah's firm boundary reflects the NT pattern: God's patience leads to repentance (Rom 2:4), but the boundary is real.</p>",
        "22": "<p>A theme: the second zāḵar prayer — 'spare me according to the greatness of your steadfast love (<em>ḥesed</em>)' — marks a shift from merit-based appeal (v14) to grace-based appeal. Nehemiah here grounds his request in God's <em>ḥesed</em> rather than in his own faithfulness. This anticipates the NT's grace-basis more directly than v14: Paul describes God's mercy in terms of <em>ḥesed</em>-equivalent grace (Eph 2:4 — 'rich in mercy'; Titus 3:5 — 'according to his own mercy he saved us'). In Christ, the full <em>ḥesed</em> of God is displayed (John 1:17).</p>",
        "23": "<p>A theme: the mixed marriages with women from Ashdod, Ammon, and Moab represent the same pattern that brought down the pre-exilic kingdom (Solomon, vv26–27). The covenant community's distinctiveness is at risk through misaligned intimate relationships. In Christ, the concern for the covenant community's distinctiveness is maintained through a different principle: 'Do not be unequally yoked with unbelievers' (2 Cor 6:14) — not ethnic separation but spiritual alignment. The boundary is real; the basis is transformed.</p>",
        "24": "<p>A theme: the children who could not speak Hebrew (<em>yəhûḏîṯ</em>) represent the loss of the language through which the Torah was transmitted. The covenant language at risk of extinction in one generation points to the irreplaceable role of transmission in covenant community. In Christ, the new 'covenant language' is the gospel — and Pentecost reverses Babel by enabling every language to speak the mighty works of God (Acts 2:5–12). The Spirit restores the transmission capacity that linguistic assimilation threatened.</p>",
        "25": "<p>A revelation of God: Nehemiah's violence — cursing, striking, pulling hair — and his oath administered 'before God' reveals the severity with which covenant fidelity was enforced in the restoration community. This is difficult to reconcile with NT ethics, but points to the seriousness of covenant betrayal. In Christ, the zeal for his bride's purity is expressed not through violence against the unfaithful but through self-sacrifice: 'Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her, that he might sanctify and cleanse her' (Eph 5:25–26).</p>",
        "26": "<p>A shadow: the Solomon precedent — 'among the many nations there was no king like him, yet even he was led into sin by foreign women' — presents wisdom corrupted by misaligned love as the archetype of covenant failure. In Christ, the archetype is reversed: he is the greater-than-Solomon (Matt 12:42 — 'something greater than Solomon is here') whose wisdom is never corrupted, whose love is never misdirected. Where Solomon's wisdom failed at the altar of foreign gods, Christ's wisdom was revealed most fully on the cross (1 Cor 1:24 — 'Christ the wisdom of God').</p>",
        "27": "<p>A theme: Nehemiah's appeal — 'are we then to listen to you and do all this great evil and be unfaithful to our God by marrying foreign women?' — frames covenant intermarriage as faithlessness (<em>māʿal</em>, treachery). The NT equivalent is spiritual unfaithfulness: James calls friendship with the world 'adultery' (Jas 4:4); Paul describes the church as betrothed to Christ and warns against the serpent's deception that would corrupt this exclusive allegiance (2 Cor 11:2–3). Covenant faithfulness to God is the theme running from Nehemiah's challenge to NT warnings against worldliness.</p>",
        "28": "<p>A shadow: the expulsion of the high priest's grandson — who married Sanballat's daughter, allying the priestly house with the enemy — is the most radical priestly defilement in the book. In Christ, the contrast is absolute: he is the High Priest who is 'holy, blameless, unstained, separated from sinners, and exalted above the heavens' (Heb 7:26). No compromise with the adversary; no defilement of the priestly office. Where the Eliashib family repeatedly yielded to Sanballat's network (vv4, 28), Christ's priesthood is eternally pure.</p>",
        "29": "<p>A theme: the third zāḵar prayer — 'Remember them, O my God, for they have defiled the priesthood' — is imprecatory (calling for judgment on the guilty) rather than petitionary. This is Nehemiah as covenant prosecutor appealing to God as judge. In Christ, divine judgment is both affirmed and transformed: Jesus is appointed judge (John 5:27; Acts 17:31), and the defilement of God's house is taken seriously. But Christ also intercedes for the guilty before the same throne (Heb 7:25; 1 John 2:1), holding prosecutor and advocate roles that Nehemiah could only separate.</p>",
        "30": "<p>A revelation of God: the summary of Nehemiah's second-term reforms — 'I purged everything foreign and assigned the priests and Levites their duties' — reveals God's ongoing concern for the covenant community's ordered purity. In Christ, this purging and ordering is accomplished definitively: Christ 'gave himself for us to redeem us from all lawlessness and to purify for himself a people for his own possession' (Titus 2:14). The people purified and ordered for service — which Nehemiah labored to achieve through repeated reform — is the result Christ accomplishes through the cross.</p>",
        "31": "<p>A theme: the final words of Nehemiah — 'Remember me, O my God, for good' — close the book with an appeal to divine memory. This last petition resonates structurally with the thief on the cross: 'Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom' (Luke 23:42). Both are appeals for divine remembrance by those who have labored in the covenant's service or clung to covenant hope at the end of life. In Christ, divine remembrance is grounded not in our goodness but in his: those written in the Lamb's book of life (Rev 21:27) are remembered eternally by grace.</p>"
    }
}


def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'nehemiah')
    merge_comm(c, NEH13)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'nehemiah', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in NEH13.values())
    print(f'nehemiah mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses for ch 13')


if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
